@node AboutTalk "What is Talk?"

	@{b}ABOUT TALK@{ub}

Talk is a replacement for the old Commodore 'Say' program.
It has 99% of the same features with a @{b}whole lot more@{ub} added.

The only thing Talk doesn't have is the Phoneme window.

This program was written basically so I could have more control over narration from shell. Talk has a whole range of commands that you will find useful, including some Time and string formatting features.

Talk is classified Giftware. See @{"License and Disclaimer" link Everyday:Introduction.guide/License}.

Have fun...

Mathew Wilson

	Contact me at:
	
	Box 6022, Halifax Street
	Adelaide SA, 5000
	AUSTRALIA

	EMail: mind@inorbit.com
	WWW:   http:www.adam.com.au/~mwilson/
@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements"

	@{b}THINGS YOU WILL NEED@{ub}

If you have, at one time in your, life bought an Amiga with a 1.x - 2.x ROM then you will be lucky enough to own the Translator library and narrator device files on disk. Sadly the old Commodore (Rot. IP) did not renew their license agreement to distribute the files needed for speaking in the later operating systems. So if you do not have the LIBS:translator.library (used to translate text into phonetical symbols)  or DEVS:narrator.device (receives  phonetical symbols and speaks them) then find someone who does.

Updates to the Translator library can be found on the Public Domain. eg. Francesco Devitt's Multilingual-speech version.

The narration capabilities were upgraded with v37 of the OS and Talk takes advantages of these. Talk requires these later versions to operate properly.
@endnode

@node Modes "Modes of operation"

	@{b}MODES OF OPERATION@{ub}

Those of you who are familiar with the 'Say' program will find similarities with Talk in the following descriptions, plus some nice extras.

 Talk has four modes of operation.

@{b}Command Line:@{ub}

This is the standard form of executing programs from a CLI / Shell. The program handles multiple identical arguments per command line. It does not use standard AmigaDOS (ReadArgs) command parsing and will interpret every argument on the command line separately in a sequential order.

@{b}Direct Entry:@{ub}

If you launch Talk with no arguments, a window (console) will appear. A list of all options will appear and you may type directly into this window. Everytime you press return, that line will be performed by Talk. Do not confuse this with a CLI / Shell where you execute programs.
To quit this mode just close the window in the standard way(s).

@{b}File:@{ub}

This mode allows you to have Talk narrate a file containing pure ascii text. If you get extremely bored one day you could tell it to narrate your 's:user-startup' file. There are examples going round of scripts that get the computer to 'sing' via a clever combination of speech parameters.

@{b}Icon Tooltypes:@{ub}

If you launch Talk from Workbench via an icon then you may place speak commands in the tooltype list. Only one command is allowed per line! Multiple commands per line is available in every other mode except this one.

	Tooltypes:
	Legal: -r
	       hello, I'm
	       -p65
	       a robot.

	Illegal: -r hello, I'm -p65 a robot.

You may open a window (console) by entering '@CON' as a tooltype. In this case the Mode will change to File Mode as consoles are handled like opened files. Therefore, @{b}no@{ub} other tooltypes will be read after a '@CON'
@endnode

@node Commands "Commands"

	@{b}TALK COMMANDS@{ub}

Every command begins with a minus sign '-'. This identifies a command and the following character will always be interpreted as a command symbol. String formatting commands begin with a '%' character.

All options can be obtained at anytime by entering a '?'. The options are:

   @{" > " link C_Mode} -r.....: Robotic voice
   @{" > " link C_Mode} -n.....: Natural voice
   @{" > " link C_Mode} -u.....: Manual voice mode
   @{" > " link C_Sex} -m.....: Male voice
   @{" > " link C_Sex} -f.....: Female voice
   @{" > " link C_Rate} -s###..: Speech rate (40 to 400)
   @{" > " link C_Pitch} -p###..: Speech pitch (65 to 320)
   @{" > " link C_Volume} -v##...: Volume (0 to 64)
   @{" > " link C_SamplingFrequency} -q#####: Sampling frequency (5000 to 28000)
 * @{" > " link C_Enthusiasm} -e###..: F0 Enthusiasm
 * @{" > " link C_Perturbation} -t##...: F0 Perturbation (0 to 255)
 * @{" > " link C_Articulation} -a###..: Articulation
 * @{" > " link C_Centralization} -c###..: Vowel centralization (0 to 100)
 * @{" > " link C_Vowels} -h#....: Centralisation vowel (1 to 11)
                 1.IY, 2.IH, 3.EH, 4.AE, 5.AA, 6.AH, 7.AO, 8.OW, 9.UH, 10.ER, 11.UW
 * @{" > " link C_FormantFrequency} -1##...: Formant frequency 1 (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_FormantFrequency} -2##...: Formant frequency 2 (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_FormantFrequency} -3##...: Formant frequency 3 (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_FormantAmplitude} -4##...: Formant amplitude 1 (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_FormantAmplitude} -5##...: Formant amplitude 2 (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_FormantAmplitude} -6##...: Formant amplitude 3 (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_AmpVoicingBias} -7##...: Amplitude of voicing bias   (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
 * @{" > " link C_AmpFricationBias} -8##...: Amplitude of frication bias (1 to 64 = -32 to +31)
   @{" > " link C_SpeakingPriority} -!###..: Speaking priority (1 to 256 = -128 to 127)
   @{" > " link C_Filename} -x file: [read] [nop]
   @{" > " link C_Default} -d[opt]: Reset setting(s) to default
   @{" > " link C_DisplaySettings} -o[opt]: Display setting(s)
        -l.....: Toggle Filter (led)
   @{" > " link C_FaceWindow} -w#....: Face Window.
   @{" > " link C_FaceCoord} -[####.: X Co-ord. Face Window (0, 1 to ...)
   @{" > " link C_FaceCoord} -]####.: Y Co-ord. Face Window (0, 1 to ...)
   @{" > " link C_GetFaceCoord} -=.....: Get the X/Y Face Window Co-ordinates
   @{" > " link C_LoadSettings} ->#....: Load settings (0, 1 to 9)
   @{" > " link C_SaveSettings} -<#....: Save settings (0, 1 to 9)
   @{" > " link C_DisplayStoredSettings} -?#....: Display stored settings (0, 1 to 9)
   @{" > " link C_SpeechString} string.: Speech string

Any numerical parameters for an option @{fg highlight}must@{fg text} be positioned directly after the command option with no spaces.  

	 	LEGAL	-p65
		ILLEGAL	-p 65

The commands may be used in any of the standard @{"modes" LINK Modes}.

* These are the extended options introduced in v37+ of the OS.
@endnode

/*** COMMANDS ***/

@node C_Mode

@{b}Mode:@{ub}

Set the speaking mode.

   -r Robotic monotone pitch.
   -n Natural pitch contour.
   -u Manual control of pitch contour using accent numbers.
   
   Default: natural
@endnode

@node C_Sex

@{b}Sex:@{ub}

Change the formant targets.

   -f (female)
   -m (male);

   Default: Male

To get a more realistic sound for each sex, you will have to change the pitch and speaking rate.
@endnode

@node C_Rate

@{b}Speech Rate:@{ub}

Set the speaking rate in words per minute.

   -s### (40 to 400) wpm

   Default: 150
@endnode

@node C_Pitch

@{b}Pitch:@{ub}
	
Baseline pitch of voice in Hertz.

   -p### (65 to 320) Hertz

   Default: 110
@endnode

@node C_Volume

@{b}Volume:@{ub}

Set the speaking volume.

	-v## (0 to 64)

   Default: 64
@endnode

@node C_SamplingFrequency

@{b}Sampling Frequency:@{ub}

Set the sampling frequency. Affects the formant tunings for unusual effects. The lower the frequency, the 'grittier' it sounds.

It is recommended that the @{"Formant Frequencies" link C_FormantFrequency} are used instead because the voice synthesiser is 'tuned' specifically to 22,000 Hertz.

   -q##### (5000 to 28000) Hertz

   Default: 22200
@endnode

@node C_Enthusiasm

@{b}Enthusiasm (F0 excursion factor) @{ub}

Control the scaling of pitch excursions used on accented syllables.
A way of controlling 'enthusiasm' in the narrator.
It is calibrated in 1/32s.

   -e### (>0)

   Default: 32
@endnode

@node C_Perturbation

@{b}Perturbation@{ub}

Amount of random low frequency modulation of pitch. Similar to what happens with an elderly voice.

   -t### (0 to 255)

   Default: 0
@endnode

@node C_Articulation

@{b}Articulation (Transition time multiplier)@{ub}

Popular interpretation of voice production says that we create speech by moving our articulators (jaw, tongue, lips, etc.) from one "target" to another. Phonemes produced by the narrator device simulate these movements acoustically by calculating their times. The Articulation control allows you to alter the percentage effect of the time durations. Values less than 100 (percent) cause a sharper response and values greater than 100 will slur the speech. A special value of 0 causes each phoneme to be joined to the next with no transitions.

   -a### percent

   Default: 100
@endnode

@node C_Centralization

@{b}Centralization (Degree of vowel centralization)@{ub}

Used in conjunction with the @{"Centralization Vowel" link C_Vowels} control to alter the degree (in percent) to which vowel targets are "pulled" towards the targets of the vowel specified by the phonetic vowel. A value of 0 causes each vowel sound to retain its own target values, whereas a value of 100 causes it to be replaced with the target of the specified phonetic vowel.

  -c### (0 to 100) percent

   Default 0
@endnode

@node C_Vowels

@{b}Centralization Vowel@{ub}

Specify a "target" phonetic vowel that is to be used in the interpolation set by @{"Centralization" link C_Centralization}.
There are 11 different phonetic vowel sounds to choose from. Instead of typing the vowel you choose its number from the specified list.

1.IY, 2.IH, 3.EH, 4.AE, 5.AA, 6.AH, 7.AO, 8.OW, 9.UH, 10.ER

  -h### (1 to 11)

   Default: '' (nothing, eg. no target interpolation)
@endnode

@node C_FormantFrequency

@{b}Formant Frequencies@{ub}

Change the tuning of one of the three formant frequencies. A formant  is a vocal tract resonance, and the frequencies of these formants move continuously as we speak. There are three formants (F1 - lowest, F2 and F3 - highest) which you can alter to drastically change the effect of the voice. It is more useful to use this than to change the overall tuning with the main @{"Frequency" link C_SamplingFrequency} control. Positive values increase the frequency and negative values decrease it.

	-(1, 2, 3)### (1 to 64)

Because negative values cannot be expressed without confusion, values of 1 to 64 represent the actual steps of -32 to 31. So 0 would be represented by the number 33.

   Default 32 (0) (for all)
@endnode

@node C_FormantAmplitude

@{b}Formant Amplitudes@{ub}

Change one of the three formant amplitudes in terms of decibels. A value of -32 will shut the formant off completely. Positive values can cause clipping.

	-(4, 5, 6)### (1 to 64)

Because negative values cannot be expressed without confusion, values of 1 to 64 represent the actual steps of -32 to 31. So 0 would be represented by the number 33.

   Default 33 (0) (for all)
@endnode

@node C_AmpVoicingBias

@{b}Amplitude of Voicing Bias@{ub}

Alter the amplitude of "voiced" sounds. These sounds occur when the vocal chords are caused to vibrate. eg. y, r, w, and m.

	-7## (1 to 64)

Because negative values cannot be expressed without confusion, values of 1 to 64 represent the actual steps of -32 to 31. So 0 would be represented by the number 33.

Positive values (34 to 64) may cause clipping. Negative values (1 to 32) are more useful.

   Default: 0 (32)
@endnode

@node C_AmpFricationBias

@{b}Amplitude of Frication Bias@{ub}

Alter the amplitude of "unvoiced" sounds. These sounds occur without the vocal chords vibrating and are made of turbulent air. eg. s, t, sh, and f.

	-8## (1 to 64)

Because negative values cannot be expressed without confusion, values of 1 to 64 represent the actual steps of -32 to 31. So 0 would be represented by the number 33.

Positive values (34 to 64) may cause clipping. Negative values (1 to 32) are more useful.

   Default: 0 (32)
@endnode

@node C_SpeakingPriority

@{b}Speaking Priority@{ub}

Control the task priority while actually speaking. The task priority remains normal until the actual act of speaking occurs. Then you may specify a separate priority using this command. 

Because negative values cannot be expressed without confusion, values of 1 to 256 represent the actual steps of -128 to 127. So 0 would be represented by the number 128.

	-!### (-128 to 127)

Default 100 (128)
@endnode

@node C_Filename

@{b}File Name:@{ub}

Change to File Mode; specify a filename to be opened and read.

   -x (file name) [READ] [NOP]

@{b}A space must be placed before the file name.@{ub}

   LEGAL   -x ram:daisy
   ILLEGAL -xram.daisy

   READ - This option causes the contents of the file to be displayed as it is read.
   
   NOP  - Turns off Command Option Parsing for the file.
          That way Talk will not attempt to interpret any '-' command specifiers in the file to be read.
@endnode

@node C_Default

@{b}Default(s):@{ub}
	
Reset one or all options to their default parameters.

   -d[option]

If you wish to reset one of the parameters to default then just type '-d' followed by the option.

	eg. '-dp' will reset the pitch to its default setting.

If you type '-d' then ALL options will be reset to their defaults.
NOTE: in the '-d' option, the character following the command will always be interpreted as an option unless it is a digit.

eg. -dg will try to reset a 'g' default which doesn't exist - ignored.
-d5 will reset all options to defaults and speak 'five'.
@endnode

@node C_DisplaySettings

@{b}Display Settings:@{ub}

Display one or all of the Command Parameter settings.

   -o[option]

Just '-o' will display all the parameters with their current settings.
'-o' followed by a command character will display the corresponding parameter.

	eg. '-op' will display the current pitch setting.
@endnode

@node C_FaceWindow

@{b}Face Window:@{ub}
	
Open or Close the Face Window.

   -w# (0, 1 to 9)
   
The Face Window contains a simple face. Its mouth moves when speaking occurs.
It can be turned on or resized by specifying a parameter of 1 to 9. The size is relative to your screen height. So a size of 9 will be maximum height. You may turn the window off by either specifying a size of 0 or quiting the program.

   eg. '-w1' open window at minimum size.
       '-w9' open window at maximum size.
       '-w0' close window if it is opened.
@endnode

@node C_FaceCoord

@{b}Face Co-ordinates@{ub}

Set the screen co-ordinates of the face window.

   -[#### (Left co-ordinate)
   -]#### (Top  co-ordinate)

Applying a value of 0 for either the Left or Top will centre the Face Window in its respective axis. If you set a value too high (eg. beyond the screen dimension) it will be adjusted.
You may check the co-ordinates at any time with the @{" -o " link C_DisplaySettings} option.

The axis values will only be verified after the window is opened.
Changing these values will only take affect when the window is re-opened.

The co-ordinates will NOT be reset with the @{" -d " link C_Default} option. This is for convenience sake. To reset them, just specify both options with a '0' parameter (-[0 -]0).

Default x = 0, y = 0 (at startup only)

see also @{" -= " link C_GetFaceCoord}
@endnode

@node C_GetFaceCoord

@{b}Get Face Co-ordinates:@{ub}

If the Face Window is @{"open" link C_FaceWindow}, then you may get its co-ordinates for later use. They are stored into the Face @{"Left and Top" link C_FaceCoord} variables so they can be saved. This is useful if you wish to manually place the opened window with the mouse and then retrieve the co-ordinates.

   -=
@endnode

@node C_LoadSettings

@{b}Load Settings:@{ub}
	
Load the speech settings from Saved or Environment file.

   -># (0, 1 to 9)
   
The @{"SaveSettings" link C_SaveSettings} command saves 9 different settings to the file "S:TalkDefaults"
You may load these individual settings with the '->' command.

There is also an Environment file called "TalkEnv" located in the ENV: drawer, which usually resides in RAM:. You may load this file as well.

To load the settings in the Environment file just specify '0' with the load command.
   eg. '->0'
   
To load the settings in the Saved file (S:TalkDefaults) just specify the number of the setting.
   eg. '->1'
       '->9'

As soon as this command is successfully called, Talk will use these settings for its speech until you alter the settings or quit the program.

* BUT, everytime Talk runs, it will load the settings in the Environment file! This way you can set some global defaults so you don't have to keep giving the parameters you want or loading a Saved setting. Something to remember is that when Talk loads a settings file (including the Environment file) and it contains a @{"Face command" link C_FaceWindow}, the Face will not appear until something is to be spoken. Imagine you had the Global defaults in the Environment file saved with the Face Window open then you called talk but didn't want any Face Window open. The Face would be automatically opened whenever Talk runs. So then you decide to put a '-w0' on the command line for Talk. Now when Talk is run you would see the Face open and close. This is undesirable, so the Face Window will not be opened when Talk reads the Environment file, only when something is to be spoken. At all other times, the Face Window will open when called.

If you've installed Talk from the Everyday Organiser Installer then you'll find that some defaults have been copied into your s: drawer. Try the following for some crazy speech:

talk ->4 these earth creatures must be exterminated
@endnode

@node C_SaveSettings

@{b}Save Settings:@{ub}
	
Save the current speech settings to a Saved or Environment file.

   -># (0, 1 to 9)

The Saved file refers to the file "S:TalkDefaults" (permanent file).
The Environment file refers to the file "ENV:TalkEnv" (temporary file).

You may save 9 different settings to the Saved file.
Only one lot of settings can be saved to the Environmental file.

When Talk runs, it uses the settings in the Environmental file for its defaults. If it can't find the file then it uses the standard system defaults.

So by saving the settings to the Saved file you can use it at a later date and saving to the Environmental file means that Talk will now use those settings for this current session.

Save to the Environmental file by specifying a '0' with the save command.
   eg. '-<0'

Save the settings to the Saved file by specifying a number from 1 to 9.
   eg. '-<1'
       '-<9'

You could load a Saved setting and save it to the Environmental file in your "s:User-Startup" to set your favourite parameters as defaults.
   eg. 'Talk ->1 -<0'
@endnode

@node C_DisplayStoredSettings

@{b}Display Stored Settings:@{ub}

You may examine the @{"Saved or Environment" link C_SaveSettings} settings for Talk with this command.

You may specify 0 for the Environment settings or 1 to 9 for one fo the Saved settings.
@endnode

@node C_SpeechString

You may enter any text to be spoken with the addition of the following Special Commands.

@{b}Special Commands:@{ub}

   %t - the current time.    eg. 12 24 PM
   %T - the current time.    eg. 12 24 & 12 O'Clock (No AM or PM postfix)
   %w - the current weekday. eg. Wednesday
   %d - the current day.     eg. Eighth
   %m - the current month.   eg. November
   %y - the current year.    eg. 19 95
   
   %n - translate a number.  eg. %n21
   
These Special Commands (begin with '%') can be inserted in your speech string at anytime. The results are not Locale sensitive, sorry. They are english translations only.

The '%n' option allows you to have Talk translate and say numbers correctly. If you wanted Talk to say the number 101 it would normally say 'one oh one.' But with the '%n' option it would say 'one hundred one.' Talk will translate numbers up to 99,999.

With the program Alarmist© by the same author you can have Talk speak the current time every hour with '%t' 
Try opening the Face Window as well and you'll have a face appear on every hour and tell you the time.

You could place Talk in your' user-startup' script to speak the day.
eg. 'c:talk today is %w, %d of %m'
@endnode

@node MultiplePersonalities

	@{b}When Faces Collide@{ub}

@{b}Q@{ub} : When I run two copies of Talk at the same time, and the Face Windows are open, the windows go all weird and I don't see the pretty mouth movements.

@{b}A@{ub} : This is caused by a quantum singularity in the near vacinity of your computer and could cause severe insanity if gone unchecked. .... I have no real answer to this other than it seems that the narrator device doesn't take to kindly to asking it about mouth movements from more than one program at once. This seems only natural considering that the narrator forces politeness and only allows one program to talk at once.

If you are using Talk with the Everyday Organiser system then you'll sometimes have occasions where Talk is called more than once at the same time and they may open Face Windows. A quick fix for this is the ARexx script 'Everyday:rexx/Talk_ARexxPort.rexx'. This script opens an ARexx port and you may send messages to it and it will pass them on to Talk. This has the effect of queuing all messages and no two Face Windows will open at once. This means that you should never call Talk directly but send the commands to the special ARexx port. Take a look at the ARexx script 'Everyday:rexx/Talk_ARexxPort.rexx' to find out more informataion.

The ARexx scripts that come with Everyday Organiser that call Talk will first check to see if the ARexx port TALK is opened otherwise talk will be called directly.
@endnode

@node History "History"

	@{b}History@{ub}

Talk is distributed with the Everyday Organiser package. The following release dates correspond to EO releases.

· @{b}v1.22@{ub} - Sixth Release (1st April 1997)

   - 100% recompiled with SAS/C 6.57.
   - Now opens Console if it can't find the icon in ICON mode rather than just quiting.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.21@{ub} - Fourth Release (31st August 1996)

   - No changes worth mentioning but you might like to check out the @{"ARexx script" link MultiplePersonalities} 'Everyday:rexx/Talk_ARexxPort'.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.20@{ub} - Third Release (8th June 1996)

   - Finally put in ALL the extended voice parameters! You'll notice a considerable increase in the amount of options available.
   - Added voice speaking priority.
   - You may now set and get the co-ordinates of the Face Window.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.10@{ub} - Second Release (27th March 1996)

   - The Face was appearing without a closed mouth sometimes (how embarassing 8).
   - The '?' command was added to allow the Saved or Environment settings to be viewed.
   - Was carelessy overwriting memory sometimes during a '-x' command. This would mostly affect the stack, but sometimes...well, do I need to say.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}v1.0@{ub} - Original Release (8th February 1996)
@endnode

